            <div type="commentary">
                 <list type="witDetail">
                    <item n="1"><p>There is no obvious interpretation of this inscription and several readings could be suggested (Forsyth 1996, 61-5). Forsyth maintains that the three initial letters MAQ are very likely to stand for 'son' in Irish (Forsyth 1996, 62) and that, more generally, <q>'the text appears to be a single male personal name and as such probably records the identity of the owner or maker (or donor if it was given as a gift)'</q> (Forsyth 1996, 66).</p>
                    </item>
                     <item n="2"><p>The use of RTI and photogrammetry conducted by Megan Kasten has confirmed the reading provided as the most feasible. The measurements taken from the 3D model enabled a more precise estimation of the average spacing between individual letters and therefore suggest that the second letter is most likely to be an O (two strokes). Similarly, given the space between the third to last and the last letter, and considering what is left of the damaged surface, the second to last character is most likely to have been an A or a B with A being linguistically more probable (Kasten 2023).</p>
                     </item>
                    <item n="3"><p>Forsyth commemorates that <q>'the Bac Mhic Connain knife-handle is one of a very small group of ogham-inscribed household objects, and as such provides important evidence for the non-monumental use of the script'</q> (Forsyth 1996, 65).</p>
                    </item>
                 </list>
            </div>
